A precious hunt for health and happiness, Pokémon Go
It's really amazing to see how the world has changed.
The fact that young people and children are no longer going out to play, preferring to spend their leisure time staring at screens, has been a matter of regret for many people over the past decade.
Pokemon Go encourages people to get off the couch and move.
The time spent looking at screens has spread from being limited to television to video games and finally to smartphones.
So it's really great to see that technology and outdoor movement are not mutually exclusive.
And of course, I'm talking about Pokémon Go, which is a character-based application that was originally created in the '90s for a video game (and then turned into a series, a deck of playing cards, and other side products).
Like so many other phenomena of popular culture, this new game was all over the map when it was released in the US, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
Later, the launch was delayed in other countries due to the intense interest that caused overloading on the servers.
Within days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
So how does it work?
In short, players can take their smartphones, go out in a GPS-tracked manner to look for Pokémon and can 'take a photo' (by taking screenshots on their phone) or 'catch' them.
A generation of younger players have joined this madness by getting off the couch to explore.
In the United States, play has led to a dramatic increase in the number of steps an average person takes each day.
Cardiogram, an app developed for Apple Watch that tracks 35,000 users, recently told the Washington Post that the percentage of people it tracked who exercised every day for 30 days rose from 45 percent to 53 percent in the first two days after the game was released.
The company doesn't know who's playing Pokémon Go; it can only see the raw data at the exercise level.
Most public health campaigns that encourage people to "take 30 minutes", "get off the couch", and "be active every day" have been ignored because most public health messages are boring and are delivered by people who seem desperate.
But the importance of exercise is understated.
People who exercise regularly are less likely to get cancer or to have depression.
Exercise, weight control, high blood pressure, diabetes, and so on, and it has a long list of benefits that I can't list here.
But the beauty of Pokémon Go is that it takes people out to do something that they enjoy.
This meets all three basic elements of health: movement, fresh air, and sunlight and entertainment.
Some people may even make new friends during the hunt.
As always, there are the cheeky game-changers looking for something to complain about.
And, of course, someone could walk in and slam the door.
What difference does it make?
A major innovation has been introduced.
Smartphone apps like Fitbit track our movement, but they don't give us a reason to exercise like this game.
The innovation will wear off and the use will diminish over time.
But because of the success of Pokémon, there will be many games that help people who go hunting to be more active, fit and healthy by combining apps and virtual reality with real-world activities.
