Wherever you are, whatever the time, the Olympics are on.
The events in Rio de Janeiro represent a competition of ambition and work that seems to be endless and inescapable.
The Olympic torch itself is like a flaming baton passed from swimmer to gymnast to triathlete.
You can't watch TV, you can't read a newspaper, or you can't sit in a coffee shop and listen to your neighbor talk about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky or Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley, who's the guy.
