It has a comic potential (like the cartoon-like shake created by the never-ending jump) but it also reflects the elegance of gymnastics and diving, two sports that it essentially combines.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish el trampolin, which means "trampoline".
The champion candidates jump almost 30 feet into the air on a large trampoline and are asked to perform a series of movements (burkma, pike and salto) before landing on their feet.
They are judged according to the official Olympic program on performance, difficulty and "flight time".
Thirty-two athletes, 16 men and 16 women, from 17 countries will compete in Rio.
The most common progression at the Olympics is the straight forward.
