In Ethiopia, a longtime ally of the United States, "A Generation in Protest"
Violent Protests in Ethiopia
In Ethiopia, protesters demanding political change have been met with fierce resistance from the government.
Witnesses say a number of protesters have received fatal gunshots in clashes with police.
Ethiopia is about to fall?
Over the past decade, it had become one of Africa's most stable nations and a solid ally for the West with its rapidly growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have spread to more and more areas, shaking the country.
In the last week alone, thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
According to human rights groups, the government's response to this has been quite brutal.
Witnesses said that police officers shot and killed many unarmed demonstrators.
Footage of the protest, believed to be from late last year or early this year, shows security officials whipping youths who are forced to put their hands against a wall.
The top UN human rights official is now calling for a full investigation.
"It's always been difficult to keep this country together, and it's going to be much harder to move forward", said Rashid Abdi, the Somali Peninsula project director for the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous nation in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is appreciated by the West.
The US military and intelligence services are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat the regional terrorist threat, particularly Somalia, and few countries in Africa have received such Western assistance.
Ethiopia's economy is growing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has been effectively improved; a new commuter train is even available in the capital Addis Ababa.
And their streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia did not display the best example of democracy (human rights groups constantly cite the repressive attitude of the government), domestic opposition was fairly limited, with dissent effectively silenced.
Many were exiled, imprisoned, killed, or driven to the most remote corners of the wilderness.
But that may be about to change.
Seyoum Teshome, a university lecturer from central Ethiopia, said, "If you suffocate people and give them no choice but to protest, these things happen".
The youth are in full protest.
A generation in protest.
There are many complaints, from land use to the pressure that the ruling coalition is putting on power.
After last year's highly controversial election, the ruling party and its allies have taken the last opposition seat and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising on the border with Eritrea, a sharp and contentious line that led to a war in June that left hundreds dead.
Analysts fear that separatist groups like the Oromo Freedom Front or the Ogaden National Freedom Front, which have been disappearing in recent years, will rearm using this turbulence.
There are several factors that explain why the bitter feelings that have been simmering beneath the surface for years are now exploding.
The first one seems innocent: smartphones.
As cheap smartphones became more common and internet service became available, only a few years ago, large numbers of Ethiopians began to communicate using social media.
Even when the government shut down access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often did during protests, most people could communicate through proxies that concealed their locations.
Several young Ethiopians said they gathered in this way for the protests.
Second, there was also increased solidarity between the Oromo and Amhara, Ethiopia's two largest ethnic groups.
The Oromo and the Amhara are not normally allies.
For a long time, the Amhara of the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia had been prominent in politics and business, exploiting the Oromo, who were mostly Muslim and lived on the plains.
But that's changing, too.
"We are moving towards gathering under one umbrella and cooperating", said Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromo leader.
The largest protests were in the Amhara and Oromo regions.
Most Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigrayan ethnic group, who make up about 6 percent of the population and dominate the army, intelligence services, commerce and politics.
The third reason behind the unrest was the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr. Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012 from an undisclosed illness.
He was thought to be a tactical genius, seeing what no one else could see.
Analysts say he's particularly adept at detecting the first signs of anxiety and discouraging and neutralizing opponents.
Mr. Abdi, a conflict analyst, said, "The current regime does not have this basic knowledge".
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was elected in relative uncertainty to replace Mr. Meles.
Unlike Mr. Meles, who hails from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr. Hailemariam is from the south.
Analysts say he has failed to win the trust of the security services, which are controlled by Tigrayans.
The result was more fear and more bloodshed.
Ethiopia's most recent experience with this kind of mess was in 2005, when thousands of people protested after analysts said the government had stolen money from a rigged election.
In the ensuing measures, many protesters were killed, although less than the previous month, and this period of turmoil passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia's leaders for visionary infrastructure planning such as the new commuter train and for their remarkable progress in fighting poverty.
But it's clear that this has not stopped the growing resentment against the Ethiopian government.
And it's getting dangerous and ethnic.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, an Amhara town, attacked businesses owned by Tigrayans, and Tigrayan hatred is also increasing on social media.
Analysts say the protests have left the United States and other Western allies in a strange position.
The U.S. government used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned aerial vehicle flights over neighboring Somalia, but it was recently reported that the base was shut down.
The West wants to support democracy openly, but it doesn't want to see its ally in a fragile region fall apart.
Mr. Abdi said, "It's like walking on a very thin rope".
