Watch out for this habit of children
Dr. Bilgin Giray, Dean of the Faculty of Dentistry, said that children relax with this reflex, making suckling a necessity because they cannot perform the chewing procedure in early life.
Dr. Giray, who lists the causes of the habit of finger sucking in children, said, "Finger sucking is a phenomenon that is seen from birth to 3-4 years of age".
Most babies suck their thumbs.
The child sucks his finger to satisfy the need to suck in infancy, and after 1-1.5 years of age, the mother sucks her finger to satisfy the desire to suck and relax.
"He can be distracted by boredom, by finger-sucking behavior when he's sleepy, when he's nervous, and when he's away from his mother", he said.
Dr. Bilgin Giray, who emphasized that the finger sucking behavior seen in older age is based on the inadequacy of the mother-child relationship and the lack of confidence in the child, explained the effects of this behavior on dental health in the following words:
Finger sucking behavior has a negative effect on the formation of the child's dental structure.
The pressure exerted during suction pushes the upper teeth forward and the lower teeth backward.
This causes the lower jaw to be positioned back, upsetting the balance of the palate and the tooth structure.
And the physiological manifestation of this is a speech disorder and a closure that looks aesthetically bad.
Noting that if not addressed early, a much more complex treatment process may be required at the age of 6 to 7 years, when permanent teeth begin to erupt, Dr. Giray said, "We can protect our children from occlusion and joint problems before the completion of jaw development".
"That is why the mouth structure of children today needs to be controlled as well as the eyes and ears", he concluded.
