NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to new NASA climate models, Venus once had conditions that were suitable for life.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to explore the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus once hosted conditions similar to those on Earth, with a warm, waterless surface and an atmosphere full of CO2.
Scientists have in the past explained Venus's slow rotation by its thick atmosphere.
But the latest estimates suggest that Venus may have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and yet it may have been slowly spinning.
The model also looked at the topography of ancient Venus.
Although it has more dry land than Earth, it may have once had sufficient water and geographical variability to protect it from rapid evaporation.
Old Venus also benefited from a 30% dimmer sun.
"In the GISS model simulation", said Anthony Del Genio, a GISS scientist, "Venus's slow rotation caused the day side to face the sun for almost two months each time".
This would heat the surface and cause rain to form thick layers of clouds that act as an umbrella to protect the surface from solar heating.
As a result, the average climate was only a few degrees cooler than it is today.
The model allowed for a similar story of evolution for Venus to be constructed, which planetary scientists had previously hypothesized.
Although it once had conditions suitable for life, Venus has been subjected to too much heat and ultraviolet light over the course of a few billion years.
The oceans evaporated and the water vapor burned away with ultraviolet light.
Hydrogen was exhausted, leaving behind only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide, a deadly greenhouse gas, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers have shared the results of the new Venus climate model in the Geophysical Investigations Papers.
