Kepler has measured the rotation of the stars in the constellation of Ulcer.
The Kepler space telescope, with its latest mission, has helped astronomers build the most complete catalog of the rotation rates of stars in the constellation Ursa Major.
The new data is helping astronomers understand why stars in the constellation rotate at different speeds and how their rotation patterns are related to planet formation.
Luisa Rebull, a research scientist at Caltech's Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis in Pasadena, said in a news release, "We hope to learn more about the relationship between a star's mass, age, and even the solar system's history when we compare our results with those of stellar clusters".
The Ulcer constellation is 445 light-years from Earth.
Most of the stars in the constellation formed 125 million years ago and are reaching new levels of maturity.
They're spinning at the highest speed they've ever been in their lives.
At peak rotation speeds, stars in this maturation phase generate large amounts of stellar wind.
These winds cause the stars to be refracted as they move through their magnetic fields.
As a star ages, its rotational speed begins to decline.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of detectable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest spin speed catalog suggests that larger stars spin faster than smaller ones.
Rebull likened the stars to dancers, stating that the larger ones performed their one-legged turns more slowly than the smaller ones.
Rebull said, "We find that the slow-spinning ones are much heavier and the fast-spinning ones are very lighter stars in the 'head' of the galaxy".
Because it is so close to the constellation of Ulster, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing stellar properties and rotation speeds.
Rebull said "the young and old Ulcer constellation provides theoretical models for stellar rotations in both directions".
There's more we want to know about how, when and why the rotation speed of stars falls, or why they leave their dancing shoes in the corner.
Rebull and colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the rotational speeds of the Ulker constellation in three new papers soon to be published in the Journal of Astronomy.
